{% extends "base.html.j2" %}
{% block title %}Worlds{% endblock %}
{% block content %}
<h1>World types</h1>
<p>Cubic Odyssey ships <strong>{{ worlds|length }} world types</strong> in <code>data/configs/worldbiomes/</code>. Each defines a set of climate biomes and pairs with a voxel-distribution file that controls which ores spawn at each depth. Most planets pick biomes procedurally (<code>m_biome*</code> as "random"), so the world type tells you what to expect more reliably than the planet name.</p>

<div class="cards">
{% for r in worlds %}
<a class="card" href="{{ root }}worlds/{{ r.slug }}.html" style="padding:0;overflow:hidden">
    <img src="{{ root }}assets/worlds/{{ r.slug }}.png" alt="" style="display:block;width:100%;height:120px;object-fit:cover;image-rendering:pixelated;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border)">
    <div style="padding:1rem 1.1rem">
        <h3 style="margin-top:0">{{ r.display }}</h3>
        <div class="count">{{ r.biome_region_count }} biomes · {{ r.ore_summary_count }} ores</div>
        {% if r.description %}<p>{{ r.description }}</p>{% endif %}
        {% if r.planets %}<p style="color:var(--text-faint);font-size:0.85em;margin-top:0.4em">Known planets: {{ r.planets|join(', ') }}</p>{% endif %}
    </div>
</a>
{% endfor %}
</div>

<div class="note">
    "Known planets" is best-effort: only Earth and the Bardwell series declare specific biome types in <code>data/configs/worlds/*.cfg</code>. The rest roll their biome list at runtime, so a "Crystalline world" is what the engine generates rather than a fixed roster.
</div>
{% endblock %}
